"Despacito" by Luis Fonsi (first) featuring Daddy Yankee (second) is the most viewed video on Vevo with over 5.5 billion views as of August 2018.

This list of most-viewed Vevo videos contains the top 100 videos with the most views of all time, as derived from Vevo charts.[1] View counts are based on the Vevo website; all of the music videos play through Vevo's partner site, YouTube, and YouTube view counts will trail those of Vevo by a few hours.

As of September 2018, a total of 81 Vevo videos have exceeded one billion views, of which 17 have exceeded two billion views, 3 have exceeded three billion views and one has exceeded five billion views.

The five fastest Vevo videos to reach one billion views are "Hello"[2][3] (87 days), "Despacito"[4][5] (97 days), "Mi Gente"[6] (103 days), "Échame la Culpa"[7] (111 days), and "Sorry"[8] (136 days).

The five fastest Vevo videos to reach two billion views are "Despacito"[4] (154 days), "Chantaje"[9] (380 days), "Sorry"[4] (394 days), "Closer (Lyric Video)"[10] (555 days), and "Hello"[4] (620 days).

The first Vevo video to reach 3 billion views is Despacito, doing so in 204 days, followed by Uptown Funk on March 31, 2018, and then Sorry on September 1, 2018.[11][12] Despacito is also the only Vevo video to reach 4 billion views, doing so in 272 days, and 5 billion views, doing so on April 5, 2018.[13][14]

As of August 2018, Taylor Swift, Katy Perry and Shakira are the only Vevo artists to have two videos that exceed two billion views.[15][16][17] Justin Bieber, Katy Perry and Shakira are the only artists to have four videos that exceed one billion views.[A]

By year of release[edit]

The following table lists the current top five most viewed Vevo videos uploaded in each year, with each total rounded to the nearest ten million views, as well as the uploader and date of publication to Vevo. Eminem, Taylor Swift, Justin Bieber and Luis Fonsi are the only artists with two videos in the top five of a single year. Eminem's "Love The Way You Lie" and "Not Afraid" are the third and fifth most viewed videos, respectively, in 2010. Swift's "Shake It Off" and "Blank Space" are the second and fifth most viewed videos, respectively, in 2014. Bieber's "Sorry" and "What Do You Mean?" are the first and fourth most viewed videos, respectively, in 2015. Fonsi's "Despacito" and "Échame la Culpa" are the first and third most viewed videos, respectively, in 2017

Notes[edit]

  1. ^ Only the uploaders of the videos are attributed, the featured artists in music videos are not counted. Videos were Vevo artists are in non Vevo videos are also not included, such as J Balvin in X and Enrique Iglesias in El Perdón.
  2. ^ "Despacito" is the currently the most viewed and the most liked YouTube video with over 5.5 billion views and 29.7 million likes as of September 2018. Despacito is also the fastest vevo video to achieve 2, 3, 4 and 5 billion views, and the first Vevo video to hit 3, 4 and 5 billion views.
  3. ^ "Uptown Funk" was the most viewed Vevo video from June 4, 2016 to October 12, 2016, as well as being the second Vevo video to hit 3 billion views.
  4. ^ "Sorry" was the most viewed Vevo video from October 12, 2016 from July 19, 2017.
  5. ^ "Sugar" is the most viewed vevo video by an all-male group.
  6. ^ "Shake It Off" is the most viewed vevo video by a female artist.
  7. ^ "Hello" is the fastest Vevo video to hit one billion views, doing so in 87 days.
  8. ^ "Blank Space" was the most viewed vevo video from October 20, 2015 to June 4, 2016.
  9. ^ "Closer" is the most viewed lyric video on Vevo.
  10. ^ "Baby" was the most viewed vevo video from July 16, 2010 to October 20, 2015, holding the record for 1923 days, a vevo record. "Baby" is also the first vevo video to hit 500 million and 1 billion views, aswell as being the most disliked YouTube video with over 9.4 million dislikes.
  11. ^ "Work from Home" is the most viewed vevo video by a female group.
  12. ^ "Axel F" is the oldest vevo video to exceed 1 billion views.
  13. ^ "Bad Romance" was the most viewed Vevo video from February 28, 2010 to July 16, 2010.
  14. ^ "Bad Romance" previously held the title of Vevo's most viewed video from April 14, 2010 to July 16, 2010.
  15. ^ "Baby" previously held the title of Vevo's most viewed video from July 16, 2010 to October 20, 2015.
  16. ^ "Uptown Funk" previously held the title of Vevo's most viewed video from June 4, 2016 to October 12, 2016.
  17. ^ "Blank Space" previously held the title of Vevo's most viewed video from October 20, 2015 to June 4, 2016.
  18. ^ "Sorry" previously held the title of Vevo's most viewed video from October 12, 2016 to July 19, 2017.
  19. ^ "Despacito" currently holds the title of Vevo's most viewed video.
  20. ^ "Despacito" became the first video to reach 3 billion views on August 4, 2017,[11] 4 billion views on October 11, 2017,[13] and 5 billion views on April 5, 2018.[14]
  21. ^ "Sorry" became the first Vevo video to reach 2 billion views on November 18, 2016.[128]
  22. ^ "Blank Space" became the first Vevo video to reach 1.5 billion views on February 20, 2016.[131][132]
  23. ^ "Baby" became to first video to reach 500 million views on March 28, 2011.[134][135] It was also the first Vevo video to reach 1 billion views on February 24, 2014.[136]
  24. ^ "Bad Romance" became the first video to reach 200 million views on May 9, 2010.[138][139]
  25. ^ "Girlfriend" was originally uploaded to YouTube by RCARecords in 2007, but was later taken down in November 2009 with 130 million views.[142][143] However, it was re-uploaded to Vevo a month before the original was deleted.[144]
